AI-researching academic. I have a somewhat classic "broad" view of AI. Not so much in the sense of strong vs. weak AI, but in the sense of AI as a rich interdisciplinary field rather than a purely technical one, where an important part of the field's research is in understanding how to formalize/computationalize vague concepts like "intelligence". A few AI folks I like in that vein: Marvin Minsky, Robert Abelson, John McCarthy, Allen Newell, Phil Agre, Erik Mueller, Michael Mateas, Ian Horswill, Jaime Carbonell.

Some interesting domains: design-support and design-automation systems, generative art, computer music, videogame possibility spaces, procedural architecture. And the history of all that stuff.

Biographically speaking, I'm an American, of recent Greek descent, who lives in Copenhagen. If you'd like to follow up about anything, email is on my website: http://www.kmjn.org/
